metadata.name: Algorithm, be my guide #164
metadata.description:
At length, I summoned the courage to approach.

-

I was worn. Months of aimless wandering have culminated in this series; a meditation on my struggles to find a direction in my life and with my art.

At times paralyzed by too many possibilities, and at other times completely void of ideas. I was lost in the depths of my thinking, overwhelmed by indecision and doubt.

Generative works are a form of process art, yet along the way I’d forgotten to “trust the process”. It was time to cede control and let each line of code light the way.

-

This project paints on a 2D canvas, pixel by pixel. I used a custom projection that blends isometric and perspective techniques, to create an uncanny viewpoint between the two. Objects are randomly generated, then an algorithm applies color mixing and position displacement to each pixel as it’s rendered.

By default the canvas has 2k pixels on its longest edge. You can change this in live view by pressing any number from 1-9. For example, pressing ‘4’ would render it with 4k pixels along the longest edge. I recommend ‘4’, but this can take up to a few minutes to render.

Press ‘s’ to save the rendered image.

metadata.name: Alienpillars #1
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: BlockonBlock #73
metadata.description:
‘BlockonBlock’ is the precursor and reserve pass for the upcoming ‘Hashway ‘69 Revisited’ collection by pixelwank. 
Free mint for pixelwank holders on tezos - After 3 days any remainders will be opened up to the public for 2tez.  

‘BlockonBlock’ was a study of rectangles following on from the use of circles in Generacci. 
Placements & building sizes are based on numbers from the fibonacci sequence. 

I had a blast making these and I hope they bring the collector as much enjoyment.

'Hashway '69 Revisited' coming soon :)

23 colour palettes 
14 colour overlays 
21% chance of extra lines
Click the image or press ‘s’ or ‘S’ in live move to save a 3000x3000 png 

Thanks for collectin’ & shoutouts to Circolors for the support <3 

R.I.F.F. 
Remember it’s for fun

metadata.name: Klimtiche #1
metadata.description:
Inspired by the 'Tree of Life' by Gustav Klimt.
Every bird comes with a default weather setting but all weather is optional.
On the keyboard:
use 's' to make it snow
use 'w' to make wind blow
use 'r' to make it rain
use 'n' to stop the animation and then again to clear all animation. 
Variables are snow intensity, rain intensity, wind speed and palette.
Made in p5.js, every tree / meadow / sky is unique in design.
Two birds is rare.
Monochrome is rare.

metadata.name: Bloc.Plan #62
metadata.description:
Working as an architect and interior designer daily, I always find that creating space is something interesting. Especially a block plan. As an architectural drawing, it serves to inform the viewer of the presence or absence of a space by composing positive and negative spaces on the site. Through this, I found out that block plan can be a captivating visual art as well.

Press [s] to save captured image

created using p5.js
dirbots - Aug22
